<graphml xmlns="http://graphml.graphdrawing.org/xmlns" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://graphml.graphdrawing.org/xmlns http://graphml.graphdrawing.org/xmlns/1.0/graphml.xsd"><key id="d6" for="edge" attr.name="source_id" attr.type="string"/>
<key id="d5" for="edge" attr.name="keywords" attr.type="string"/>
<key id="d4" for="edge" attr.name="description" attr.type="string"/>
<key id="d3" for="edge" attr.name="weight" attr.type="double"/>
<key id="d2" for="node" attr.name="source_id" attr.type="string"/>
<key id="d1" for="node" attr.name="description" attr.type="string"/>
<key id="d0" for="node" attr.name="entity_type" attr.type="string"/>
<graph edgedefault="directed"><node id="&quot;TROU NOIR&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A 'black hole' or memory lapse is described as a potential consequence of stage fright and cognitive sidération during a discussion or performance."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-f736994c87df07b89d48f895b0862dfe</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SORBONNE UNIVERSITÉ&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A prestigious university in Paris, France. Richard Lévy holds a professorship in neurology at this institution."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0f56e3dd7a20b73152355d96bd750de5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;AFRIQUE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Africa is mentioned as one of the habitats of elephants in Richard Lévy's explanation of semantic knowledge distribution in the brain."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cef3ed8b278fc8ecffbe23ed1293fa7a</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;INTERVIEW&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The interview between Étienne Klein and Richard Lévy focuses on neurological conditions, discussing symptoms like anosognosia, the role of the prefrontal cortex, and a case of semantic dementia."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cef3ed8b278fc8ecffbe23ed1293fa7a</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LIBRE-ARBITRE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Free will is a central topic in Richard Lévy's book and the conversation, discussed in relation to how the brain processes values and makes decisions, suggesting a neurobiological underpinning."&lt;SEP&gt;"Free will is the philosophical concept of the ability to make choices free from certain constraints, discussed as the central topic of Richard Lévy's book and the conversation."&lt;SEP&gt;"The philosophical concept of free will, central to the discussion, debated between being an absolute freedom or an illusion constrained by biological, physical, and cognitive factors."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e9f17dfb333219cce1353f879de8deae&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;TEMPS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Time is discussed as a dimension that humans can manipulate mentally by buffering the present, recalling the past, and anticipating the future, which is essential for abstract thought."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DISCUSSION SUR LE LIBRE-ARBITRE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The main conversation event between Étienne Klein and Richard Lévy, analyzing free will from philosophical and neuroscientific perspectives, referencing contrasting viewpoints."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e9f17dfb333219cce1353f879de8deae</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;AUTOMATISMES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Automatic actions or knowledge, likened to major highways in the brain, formed through repetition and resilient until late in a disease."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ÉQUIPE DE RICHARD LÉVY&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Richard Lévy's research team, which contributes to learning new things about the brain and neurodegenerative diseases."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-ef9367e0b21550ebdb56758dc0bde39a</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DESCARTES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"René Descartes, a philosopher referenced in the title of Stéphane Charpier's book 'Le cauchemar de Descartes' and whose dualist philosophy on mind and free will is contrasted with Spinozist and neuroscientific views."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e9f17dfb333219cce1353f879de8deae</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;NÉOCORTEX&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The most recent evolutionary part of the cerebral cortex, composed of six distinct layers of neurons with specific connections. It is a key structure in higher-order brain functions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0f56e3dd7a20b73152355d96bd750de5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SPINOZA&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A philosopher referenced by Richard Lévy, whose ideas (Spinozism) are mentioned as the foundation for the argument that free will is an illusion and that humans are constrained by deterministic factors."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e9f17dfb333219cce1353f879de8deae</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MARC&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Marc is a 58-year-old patient suffering from frontotemporal dementia, exhibiting behavioral changes as described by Richard Lévy."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-ef9367e0b21550ebdb56758dc0bde39a</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MARTINE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Martine is a patient described as suffering from semantic dementia, a condition that impairs her ability to access conceptual information such as her birthdate."&lt;SEP&gt;"Martine is a patient with semantic dementia described by Richard Lévy. She is seen only once, highlighting the progressive and untreatable nature of her condition."&lt;SEP&gt;"Patient described as having semantic dementia. She illustrates the condition's effects, such as being unable to access the concept of her birthdate despite intact automatic functions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cef3ed8b278fc8ecffbe23ed1293fa7a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-aed49b1357eab65a81ac84db1c48e9f8</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ANOSOGNOSIE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Anosognosia is a symptom where patients are unaware of their own illness. It is mentioned in the context of a neurodegenerative disease and is famously associated with a French president."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cef3ed8b278fc8ecffbe23ed1293fa7a</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DÉSINHIBITION COMPORTEMENTALE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Behavioral disinhibition is a symptom resulting from prefrontal cortex dysfunction, leading to inappropriate behaviors."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cef3ed8b278fc8ecffbe23ed1293fa7a</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CONNAISSANCES SÉMANTIQUES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Semantic knowledge accumulated over time, which shapes an individual's perception and understanding of the world."&lt;SEP&gt;"Semantic knowledge, described as part of the brain's network of knowledge, with simpler concepts forming stronger, more automatic connections."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SAINT-AUGUSTIN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Saint Augustine, a philosopher and theologian referenced by Richard Lévy as holding a view on free will that is totally opposed to the Spinozist perspective presented by Stéphane Charpier."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e9f17dfb333219cce1353f879de8deae</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;YVES ROBERT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Yves Robert is a French filmmaker and actor referenced in the context of semantic knowledge, specifically associated with the phrase 'un éléphant ça trompe énormément'."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cef3ed8b278fc8ecffbe23ed1293fa7a</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MENTALISATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Mentalization is the capacity to represent another person's feelings or thoughts, exemplified by understanding someone's emotional state from facial expressions."&lt;SEP&gt;"Mentalization is the capacity to represent what another person is feeling or thinking. It is a step beyond imitation, exemplified by interpreting another's emotional state from their facial expressions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LOBES TEMPORAUX (TEMPORAL LOBES)&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Brain regions located behind the temples and ears. Their anterior parts host a critical 'super hub' for integrating semantic knowledge."&lt;SEP&gt;"The temporal lobes are brain regions located behind the temples and ears; their anterior parts contain a critical hub for semantic knowledge integration."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-aed49b1357eab65a81ac84db1c48e9f8</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;EXPÉRIENCE SUR LE SINGE / MONKEY EXPERIMENT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A scientific experiment described by Richard Lévy involving a monkey, a reward, and an opaque screen, used to demonstrate the activity of 'delay neurons' in the prefrontal cortex during a waiting period, serving as evidence for internal deliberation before action."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e9f17dfb333219cce1353f879de8deae</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;VALEURS CONTEXTUALISÉES/RELATIVISÉES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Contextualized or relativized values are valuations that change based on circumstances, time, and cost-benefit analysis, such as coming to value turnips during a famine."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CIVILISATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Civilization refers to the fragile top layer of human behavior, encompassing social norms and morality, which depends on the healthy function of the prefrontal cortex. It can be lost with age or disease."&lt;SEP&gt;"Civilization refers to the layer of social norms and morality that depends on the prefrontal cortex and can be lost with aging or disease."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;TRAJECTOIRE DE VIE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Life trajectory, described by Richard Lévy as a constraint where one's current place and time are determined by all preceding actions, limiting the margin of action."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e9f17dfb333219cce1353f879de8deae</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SUPER HUB / STATION LÉAL-CHÂTELET&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The metaphorical major interchange station in the brain's information network. It integrates auditory, visual, and linguistic knowledge, and is the primary site damaged in semantic dementia."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-aed49b1357eab65a81ac84db1c48e9f8</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CHOCOLAT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Chocolate is used repeatedly as an example of a concrete value or reward that the brain processes."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;FRANÇOIS MITTERRAND&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"François Mitterrand is a former French president who is referenced in connection with the term 'anosognosia', making it famous."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cef3ed8b278fc8ecffbe23ed1293fa7a</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;INSTITUT DU CERVEAU&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A research institute focused on brain studies. Richard Lévy is a researcher at this institute and leads the Frontlab team there."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0f56e3dd7a20b73152355d96bd750de5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;NAVETS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Turnips are used as an example of a food item whose perceived value can be transformed from negative to positive based on context and need, such as during a famine."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CORTEX&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Refers to the cerebral cortex, the outer layer of the brain's hemispheres composed of gray matter and billions of neurons. It is organized in layers and is central to higher brain functions. Also the title of Richard Lévy's book."&lt;SEP&gt;"The title of Richard Lévy's book, focusing on the brain and its functions."&lt;SEP&gt;"Title of Richard Lévy's book, focusing on the brain and promoted during the conversation."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0f56e3dd7a20b73152355d96bd750de5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LOIS PHYSIQUES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Physical laws, listed by Richard Lévy as one of the fundamental constraints (like gravity and temperature) that humans are subject to, limiting absolute freedom of action."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e9f17dfb333219cce1353f879de8deae</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;COMPORTEMENTS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Behaviors, categorized by Richard Lévy into automatic reactions and those involving delayed action through time buffering."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;TOILE D'ARAIGNÉE (RÉSEAU DE CONNAISSANCES)&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The spider web metaphor for the brain's network of knowledge, featuring thick, strong connections and thinner, more tenuous ones."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;IRM&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Imaging technology (MRI) cited as a tool for detecting structural brain lesions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SALÉ&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Salty taste is presented as a basic, absolute biological value that drives action because it is necessary for survival."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PORTE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A door used as an example by Richard Lévy of an automatic behavioral response: turning one's head upon hearing it open unexpectedly."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;APATHIE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Apathy is a symptom mentioned in the context of neurodegenerative diseases, characterized by an inability to initiate voluntary behaviors."&lt;SEP&gt;"Apathy is a symptom of frontotemporal dementia involving the inability to initiate voluntary behaviors."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cef3ed8b278fc8ecffbe23ed1293fa7a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ef9367e0b21550ebdb56758dc0bde39a</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SIGNAL ÉLECTRIQUE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Electrical signal described as a fundamental component of thought and action in the brain."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DISCUSSION RADIO&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The radio discussion is the event in which Étienne Klein interviews Richard Lévy, forming the context for the entire transcribed dialogue on neuroscience topics."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-f736994c87df07b89d48f895b0862dfe</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MALADIE NEURODÉGÉNÉRATIVE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A progressive disease (likely dementia) that affects knowledge networks and automatic actions, mentioned in the context of cognitive decline."&lt;SEP&gt;"Neurodegenerative disease is a type of condition characterized by progressive neuron degeneration, as seen in frontotemporal dementia."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ef9367e0b21550ebdb56758dc0bde39a</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LEURS COPAINS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The peers ('copains') of adolescents are mentioned as the source of new social norms that adolescents adopt, replacing parental norms during their development."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SIGNAL CHIMIQUE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Chemical signal described as a fundamental component of thought and action in the brain."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PLAN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The plan refers to the experiment described where an animal must learn to choose a side (left or right) based on reward location, and its performance is tested by destroying specific brain areas."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-f736994c87df07b89d48f895b0862dfe</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ÉLECTRONS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Electrons are mentioned as an example of things that are not directly perceivable but have been discovered through the brain's abstract capabilities."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ONDES GRAVITATIONNELLES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Gravitational waves are mentioned as an example of things that are not directly perceivable but have been discovered through the brain's abstract capabilities."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;NEURODEGENERATIVE DISEASES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A class of diseases that progressively affect intellectual functions, such as Alzheimer's disease. Richard Lévy and his team treat patients suffering from these conditions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0f56e3dd7a20b73152355d96bd750de5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;L'ENFANT LYCÉEN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The high school child is the subject in Richard Lévy's example of mentalization. Their facial expression upon seeing their Bac exam results conveys their emotional state to the observing mother."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MICHEL LÉVY&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Michel Lévy is mentioned briefly by Étienne Klein as the subject of a follow-up question, redirecting the conversation from free will to a new topic about stage fright."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-f736994c87df07b89d48f895b0862dfe</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CONSULTATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A medical consultation where a patient is brought, used as an example to explain lack of understanding of social norms."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SUPER HUB (STATION LÉAL-CHÂTELET)&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A metaphorical 'super hub' or major interchange station in the brain's information network, located in the anterior temporal lobes, integrating auditory, visual, and linguistic knowledge."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-aed49b1357eab65a81ac84db1c48e9f8</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LÉSIONS STRUCTURELLES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Structural brain damage cited as one cause of cognitive disorders."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;OBSTACLE (SUR UNE ROUTE NEURONALE)&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"An obstacle blocking a neural pathway, used to explain how information flow is impeded in neurodegenerative disease."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ÊTRE BIOLOGIQUE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A biological being; Richard Lévy uses this term to describe an entity living only in the immediate present, unable to perceive beyond concrete reality."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SUBJECTIVITÉ&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Subjectivity is a component of perception; Richard Lévy discusses how individual experiences shape our largely subjective view of the world."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MODÈLE COMPORTEMENTAL BASIQUE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Basic behavioral model refers to the framework present in all animal species where behavior is driven by seeking rewards and avoiding punishments."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;THÉORIE DE L'ESPRIT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Theory of mind is the ability to infer others' mental states, allowing for multiple levels of inference about what others think."&lt;SEP&gt;"Theory of mind is the cognitive ability to infer what another person is thinking, allowing for multiple levels of reasoning (e.g., 'what does X think Y thinks?'). It underpins the cognitive level of empathy."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LOBES TEMPORAUX&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The temporal lobes are brain regions also affected in frontotemporal dementia, associated with memory and emotion."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-ef9367e0b21550ebdb56758dc0bde39a</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PSYCHIATRIE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Medical field dedicated to the diagnosis and treatment of mental illnesses."&lt;SEP&gt;"The medical field dealing with mental illnesses and behavioral disorders."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MÈRE THÉRÉSA&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Mother Teresa is mentioned as an example of altruism and acting in accordance with abstract values, illustrating how such values can motivate self-sacrificing behavior."&lt;SEP&gt;"Mother Teresa was a Catholic nun and missionary known for founding the Missionaries of Charity and dedicating her life to serving the poor and sick in Calcutta, India."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LES ADOLESCENTS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Adolescents are described by Richard Lévy as individuals whose brains are not fully matured ('malades qui s'ignorent'). They are characterized by rebelling against parental norms and adopting the norms of their peers."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CONSTRUCTION DES NORMES SOCIALES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The process of building social norms over time, parallel to brain development, involving mechanisms like imitation and empathy."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;EXPÉRIENCES ANTÉRIEURES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Past experiences are cited by Richard Lévy as elements that shape an individual's subjective perception of the world."&lt;SEP&gt;"Past experiences are the accumulated personal history and knowledge that shape and influence an individual's perception and interpretation of new sensory information."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cd188b1ca7e68272621793f69c55fafa&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ÉVOLUTION DES ESPÈCES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Evolution of species is the process that explains the development of the cold part of the prefrontal cortex in primates and humans."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PERMIS DE CONDUIRE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The driving license is a legal document that permits individuals to operate a vehicle. The discussion revolves around whether the legal age for obtaining it should be lowered, considering the incomplete cognitive development of adolescents."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5a0e0f31ff75981ae7f4e27b231396b7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HÉMISPHÈRES CÉRÉBRAUX&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The cerebral hemispheres (left and right) that form the bulk of the brain. The cortex is described as the superficial layer covering these hemispheres."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0f56e3dd7a20b73152355d96bd750de5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;OBJECTIVITÉ&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Objectivity is mentioned as being difficult to separate from subjectivity within a perceptual system we cannot exit."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;NEURONES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Nerve cells whose activity in the prefrontal cortex enables humans to buffer time, deliberate, and imagine abstract concepts."&lt;SEP&gt;"Neurons are nerve cells that degenerate in neurodegenerative diseases such as frontotemporal dementia."&lt;SEP&gt;"Neurons are the fundamental cells of the nervous system that transmit electrical and chemical signals, forming complex networks within the brain."&lt;SEP&gt;"Neurons, the primary nerve cells that constitute the brain's gray matter. They are mentioned as the billions of cells contained within the cerebral cortex."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0f56e3dd7a20b73152355d96bd750de5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cd188b1ca7e68272621793f69c55fafa&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ef9367e0b21550ebdb56758dc0bde39a</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PARTIE HAUTE DU CORTEX PRÉFRONTAL&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The high part of the prefrontal cortex, physically at the top of the skull, is where the cold part is located."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;FONCTIONS VÉGÉTATIVES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Vegetative functions are internal, automatic bodily functions such as hunger and thirst, managed by the hot part of the prefrontal cortex."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ÂME&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The soul, in this context, refers to the hot aspect of the prefrontal cortex that regulates internal sensations, emotions, mood, and motivation. It influences thought and behavior based on internal states and values."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5a0e0f31ff75981ae7f4e27b231396b7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LA CONVERSATION SCIENTIFIQUE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The event or program during which Étienne Klein interviews Richard Lévy."&lt;SEP&gt;"The name of the podcast episode hosted by Étienne Klein. It is a scientific conversation program where topics like brain function are discussed."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0f56e3dd7a20b73152355d96bd750de5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SAUT ONTOLOGIQUE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Ontological leap refers to the evolutionary jump mentioned between mammals and primates regarding the development of the cold part of the prefrontal cortex."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ADULTE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"An adult is described as an individual considered to be in full control of their cognitive functions, representing an age of maximum cognitive capacity roughly between 30 and 70 years old, used as a contrast point to adolescent development."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5a0e0f31ff75981ae7f4e27b231396b7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SIGNAL ÉLECTRIQUE / CHIMIQUE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Electrical and chemical signals are mentioned as the fundamental material basis of all thought and action in the brain, connecting neural activity to mental processes and potential dysfunctions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-f736994c87df07b89d48f895b0862dfe</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;NEURONES MIROIRS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Mirror neurons are brain structures involved in imitation and action understanding, contributing to empathy."&lt;SEP&gt;"Mirror neurons are brain structures involved in imitation, reacting not only when one performs an action but also when observing others perform actions."&lt;SEP&gt;"Mirror neurons are structures in the brain associated with action and imitation. They react not only when an individual performs an action like moving or speaking, but also when observing another person perform that same action."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;OPÉRATION COMPUTATIONNELLE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Computational operation refers to the cold, reasoned processing performed by the cold part of the prefrontal cortex, as directed by the valuation from the hot part."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;NORMES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Norms are standards of behavior. In the text, they refer to the social rules adolescents adhere to, specifically the shift from parental norms to peer norms, which is presented as a typical characteristic of adolescence."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5a0e0f31ff75981ae7f4e27b231396b7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ÉTIENNE KLEIN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A speaker in the conversation who explains the brain's semantic network using the metaphor of a spider web or subway system, focusing on the impact of semantic dementia."&lt;SEP&gt;"Host of the podcast 'La conversation scientifique'. He introduces the episode's topic about how the brain works and questions the role of the brain in perception and cognition."&lt;SEP&gt;"Host of the scientific conversation 'La Conversation Scientifique'; interviews Richard Lévy about neurology and mental illnesses."&lt;SEP&gt;"Host of the scientific conversation, asks questions about neurology and mental illnesses."&lt;SEP&gt;"Host or moderator of the discussion, introduces the topic of free will and references another author's work."&lt;SEP&gt;"Étienne Klein interviews Richard Lévy about neurological diseases, specifically asking about the case of Martine and the nature of semantic dementia."&lt;SEP&gt;"Étienne Klein is a participant in a conversation about the brain and perception, asking questions and engaging with the topics discussed."&lt;SEP&gt;"Étienne Klein is a physicist and interviewer who engages Richard Lévy in a discussion about the prefrontal cortex, adolescence, and the debate on lowering the legal driving age. He prompts Lévy to elaborate on his ideas."&lt;SEP&gt;"Étienne Klein is an interlocutor who asks Richard Lévy about the brain's capacity to discover things beyond sensory perception, such as electrons and black holes."&lt;SEP&gt;"Étienne Klein is an interviewer and moderator who engages in a scientific dialogue with Richard Lévy, posing questions about neuroscience concepts such as free will, stage fright, and mental illnesses."&lt;SEP&gt;"Étienne Klein is an interviewer asking questions about brain function and social norms, engaging with Richard Lévy on these topics."&lt;SEP&gt;"Étienne Klein is the interviewer conducting a conversation about neuroscience, empathy, and brain development. He poses questions to Richard Lévy about the brain's maturity and the author's provocative statements regarding adolescents."&lt;SEP&gt;"Étienne Klein is the interviewer conducting a conversation with Richard Lévy about brain function and medical cases."&lt;SEP&gt;"Étienne Klein is the interviewer in the conversation, who prompts Richard Lévy with questions about values, free will, and uses examples like turnips to explore the mechanisms of preference change."&lt;SEP&gt;"Étienne Klein is the interviewer questioning Richard Lévy about neuroscience topics such as empathy, mirror neurons, and brain development."&lt;SEP&gt;"Étienne Klein is the interviewer who asks Richard Lévy questions about the prefrontal cortex and decision-making, and references historical figures like Jean Moulin."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e9f17dfb333219cce1353f879de8deae&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0f56e3dd7a20b73152355d96bd750de5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ef9367e0b21550ebdb56758dc0bde39a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736994c87df07b89d48f895b0862dfe&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5a0e0f31ff75981ae7f4e27b231396b7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cef3ed8b278fc8ecffbe23ed1293fa7a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cd188b1ca7e68272621793f69c55fafa&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-aed49b1357eab65a81ac84db1c48e9f8</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;TROUBLES DU COMPORTEMENT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Behavioral disorders are symptoms of frontotemporal dementia, including inappropriate social behavior, neglect, lack of empathy, and apathy."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-ef9367e0b21550ebdb56758dc0bde39a</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;FONCTIONS FROIDES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Cold functions refer to cognitive processes such as planning, reasoning, and cold computation, attributed to the cold part of the prefrontal cortex."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CONTEXTE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Context refers to the situation or environment that is decoded by the hot part of the prefrontal cortex to assign value and guide appropriate behavioral responses."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;JAPON&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Japon is mentioned as an analogy: being in Japan without knowing ideograms is compared to a patient not understanding social norms."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CELLULES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Biological cells, specifically neurons, whose activity in the prefrontal cortex can be measured and is linked to deliberation and imagination."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PARTIE FROIDE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The cold part of the prefrontal cortex, located at the top of the head, is responsible for cold functions like planning and reasoning, and is highly developed in humans."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CAPACITÉS D'INHIBITION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Inhibition capacities refer to the cognitive ability to control impulses. The text discusses these as not being fully developed in young adults, which is used as an argument against lowering the legal driving age."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5a0e0f31ff75981ae7f4e27b231396b7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;QUARKS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Quarks are mentioned as an example of things that are not directly perceivable but have been discovered through the brain's abstract capabilities."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ÉLÉPHANT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"An elephant is a large mammal used as an example to illustrate how the brain infers complete objects from partial sensory information, such as seeing only its trunk."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cd188b1ca7e68272621793f69c55fafa</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ALBIN MICHEL&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A publishing house that published Richard Lévy's book 'Cortex'."&lt;SEP&gt;"Publishing house that released Richard Lévy's book 'Cortex'."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;VALEURS ABSOLUES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Absolute values are automatic, hardwired preferences such as for sweet and salty tastes, processed automatically by the brain without conscious deliberation."&lt;SEP&gt;"Absolute values are inherent, unchanging valuations processed automatically by the brain, such as the basic preference for sweet tastes over bitter ones."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ALZHEIMER'S DISEASE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A specific neurodegenerative disease mentioned as an example of the conditions treated by Richard Lévy's medical team. It affects intellectual functions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0f56e3dd7a20b73152355d96bd750de5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LOBE FRONTAL&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The frontal lobe is a brain region affected in frontotemporal dementia, involved in behavior and decision-making."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-ef9367e0b21550ebdb56758dc0bde39a</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;NEUROPSYCHIATRIE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"An interdisciplinary field combining neurology and psychiatry to treat patients at the boundary of both disciplines."&lt;SEP&gt;"Interdisciplinary field combining neurology and psychiatry to treat patients at the boundary of both disciplines."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ÂGE LÉGAL&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The legal age is the state-mandated age requirement for certain activities, specifically discussed in the context of obtaining a driving permit. The debate centers on whether it should be lowered given adolescent brain development."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5a0e0f31ff75981ae7f4e27b231396b7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CORTEX FRONTAL&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The frontal cortex is a region of the brain mentioned as reaching maturation around 28, 30, or 35 years of age. It is a key structure for cognitive control and is contrasted with the more specific prefrontal cortex."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5a0e0f31ff75981ae7f4e27b231396b7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;AUTOROUTES (CONNAISSANCES)&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Major highways, a metaphor for well-established, automatic knowledge pathways in the brain that are resistant to disruption."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;EXPOSÉ&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"An exposé is mentioned as an example of a stressful situation that can trigger stage fright, where cognitive performance can be hampered by overwhelming emotions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-f736994c87df07b89d48f895b0862dfe</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;RÉSEAU D'INFORMATION CÉRÉBRAL (BRAIN INFORMATION NETWORK)&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Described as a spider web or vast subway network where different 'stations' process specific aspects of information (color, shape, word, sound) which are then interconnected."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-aed49b1357eab65a81ac84db1c48e9f8</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PROPRIÉTÉS PHYSIQUES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Physical properties, such as those of electrons or quarks, which are not apparent to the eye but can be discovered through abstract thought."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;YEUX&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Eyes are sensory organs that capture visual stimuli and transmit signals to the brain for processing into visual perception."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cd188b1ca7e68272621793f69c55fafa</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SERRMENT DE MAIN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Handshake is a social gesture that involves complex brain activity and motor control, used as an example to illustrate automatic versus deliberate actions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-ef9367e0b21550ebdb56758dc0bde39a</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;RÉALITÉ INCARNÉE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"'Embodied reality' refers to Richard Lévy's point that the ability to open time and imagine is grounded in measurable, physical brain activity, not just a concept."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DÉMENCE SÉMANTIQUE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Semantic dementia is a type of dementia characterized by loss of semantic knowledge. It is explained by Richard Lévy using the example of an elephant, where knowledge about its attributes is stored distributedly in the brain."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cef3ed8b278fc8ecffbe23ed1293fa7a</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SYSTÈME&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The biological and perceptual system, referenced by Richard Lévy, from which humans cannot exit and through which we understand the world."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MATIÈRE GRISE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Gray matter, the brain tissue primarily consisting of neuronal cell bodies. It is described as the main component of the cerebral cortex."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0f56e3dd7a20b73152355d96bd750de5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CORTEX CÉRÉBRAL&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The cerebral cortex is the outer layer of the brain, consisting of six layers of neurons, responsible for higher cognitive functions such as thought, perception, and memory."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cd188b1ca7e68272621793f69c55fafa</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;FRONTLAB&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A specialized research team within the Institut du cerveau, led by Richard Lévy. It focuses on studying the prefrontal cortex and translating research into clinical applications."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0f56e3dd7a20b73152355d96bd750de5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;JULIEN MOULET&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Responsible for the realization and mise en monde of the scientific conversation."&lt;SEP&gt;"Responsible for the technical realization and 'mise en monde' of the scientific conversation."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MONDE MATÉRIEL&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The material world, which Richard Lévy says humans can transcend through imagination and abstract thought enabled by the prefrontal cortex."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;NEUROLOGIE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Medical discipline studying the nervous system; discussed as providing a biological framework for understanding mental processes and disorders."&lt;SEP&gt;"The medical discipline focusing on the nervous system, particularly brain functions and dysfunctions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;GESTES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Gestures, such as shaking hands, mentioned at the end of the text as an example of human action."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ENFANT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Child, referenced to explain that the brain, especially the prefrontal cortex, is not finished at birth and develops over many years, allowing learning and structuring."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;RÉSISTANCE (HISTORIQUE)&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The Resistance refers to the historical event and movement during World War II, cited here in the example of Jean Moulin's actions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SUCRÉ&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Sweet taste is presented as a basic, absolute biological value that drives action because it is necessary for survival."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;COUCHE DE CIVILISATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The 'layer of civilization' is a specific term used for the set of social norms and moral functions supported by the prefrontal cortex. It is described as the last and most fragile layer added to human cognition."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;NORMES SOCIALES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Social norms are rules and expectations constructed during brain development, involving empathy and mirror neuron systems."&lt;SEP&gt;"Social norms are standards of behavior derived from beliefs and values, constructed at the highest level of abstraction. They are maintained by the prefrontal cortex and influence behavior, especially during adolescence."&lt;SEP&gt;"Social norms are standards of behavior derived from beliefs and values, shaped by the prefrontal cortex and influential in adolescence."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;FONCTIONS CHAUDES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hot functions refer to processes like motivation, emotion regulation, and vegetative functions (e.g., hunger, thirst), attributed to the hot part of the prefrontal cortex."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;FONCTIONS FRONTALES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Frontal functions are the cognitive abilities governed by the prefrontal cortex. They include empathy and the maintenance of social norms, and they naturally decline with aging."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MAMMIFÈRES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A class of animals; Richard Lévy notes that the particular prefrontal cortex feature is absent in other mammal species."&lt;SEP&gt;"Mammals are animals that possess the hot part of the prefrontal cortex, as discussed in the evolutionary context of brain development."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PATIENT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A hypothetical patient in a consultation who does not understand social norms and considers the person who brought them as the one who is ill, used as an analogy."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;THIERRY BEAUCHAMP&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Collaborator on the production of the scientific conversation."&lt;SEP&gt;"Collaborator on the scientific conversation, involved in its production."&lt;SEP&gt;"Thierry Beauchamp is mentioned as a technician or listener who is part of the extended audience for the conversation, representing a higher-order level of inference in the 'theory of mind' explanation."&lt;SEP&gt;"Thierry Beauchamp is mentioned as a technician or participant listening to the conversation between Étienne Klein and Richard Lévy."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;VIEILLISSEMENT NORMAL&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Normal aging is described as a physiological process that leads to a decline in frontal lobe functions, including a reduction in empathetic capacities, even in non-pathological cases."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;OCÉANS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The oceans are mentioned as an environment humans might imagine exploring despite not having gills, representing a realm of abstract possibility."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ROUTES SECONDAIRES (CONNAISSANCES)&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Secondary roads, a metaphor for less stable, more abstract knowledge pathways in the brain that are easily blocked."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;RÉFLEXION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The act of reflection, made possible by the brain's ability to buffer the present and consider possibilities."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PRIMUM NOVINS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A Latin-derived term used in the text to denote the primary, fundamental driving force of behavior, which is the attribution of value."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SERIAL KILLER&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A serial killer is an example used to illustrate a person who lacks empathy (hot part) but retains cold reasoning abilities, capable of planning actions coldly."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SYSTÈME NERVEUX&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The nervous system is entirely involved in the handshake gesture, coordinating muscle contractions and sensory feedback."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-ef9367e0b21550ebdb56758dc0bde39a</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CAPTEURS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Sensors, such as the eyes and ears, are organs that capture external stimuli and transform them into neural signals for the brain to interpret."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cd188b1ca7e68272621793f69c55fafa</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;RIVIÈRE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A river is a natural watercourse mentioned in the example of an elephant's trunk emerging from it, serving as a geographical context for perception."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cd188b1ca7e68272621793f69c55fafa</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DÉCISION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Decision-making is a cognitive process guided by the attempt to obtain rewards or avoid punishments, according to Richard Lévy's explanation."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CÔNES ET BÂTONNETS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The photoreceptor cells in the retina (cones and rods) that send partial visual information to the brain. They are mentioned as the source of incomplete data that the brain processes to form a complete visual image."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0f56e3dd7a20b73152355d96bd750de5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;FONCTIONS AUTOMATIQUES (AUTOMATIC FUNCTIONS)&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Routine actions and behaviors that do not require access to full semantic knowledge, allowing patients with semantic dementia to maintain a degree of autonomy, such as making coffee."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-aed49b1357eab65a81ac84db1c48e9f8</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;NOYAUX&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Nuclei are clusters of neurons located deep within the brain, involved in various functions such as relaying and processing neural signals."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cd188b1ca7e68272621793f69c55fafa</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DYSFONCTIONNEMENTS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Functional impairments in the brain that can cause disorders without visible lesions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SIX COUCHES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The six layers refer to the laminar structure of the cerebral cortex, with each layer having specific neuronal connections crucial for information processing."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cd188b1ca7e68272621793f69c55fafa</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PUNITION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Punishment is a negative value attributed to situations that motivates behavior to avoid them."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BAC&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The Baccalauréat (Bac) is the French national secondary school exit exam. Its results are posted publicly, and it serves as a real-world example in the text to illustrate the concept of mentalization."&lt;SEP&gt;"The Baccalauréat is a French national exam whose results are posted publicly; used as an example to illustrate mentalization when a mother reads her child's results."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DÉLIBÉRATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Deliberation, a cognitive process highlighted by Richard Lévy. It involves 'freezing the present' to introduce other dimensions of reflection, occurs in real time before action, and is evidenced by neural activity, argued to provide degrees of freedom."&lt;SEP&gt;"Deliberation, described as a process enabled by opening up time between perception and action, allowing for analysis and decision-making."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e9f17dfb333219cce1353f879de8deae&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LIVRE (THE BOOK)&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The literary work in which the described conversation with the patient Martine is recorded, serving as the source of the case study."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-aed49b1357eab65a81ac84db1c48e9f8</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;OREILLES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Ears are sensory organs that capture auditory stimuli and transmit signals to the brain for processing into auditory perception."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cd188b1ca7e68272621793f69c55fafa</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;TROMPE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The trunk is a distinctive elongated appendage of an elephant, used as an example of partial visual information that the brain can use to infer the whole animal."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cd188b1ca7e68272621793f69c55fafa</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SYDNEY&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A city mentioned as a geographic example of a specific place and time, illustrating how one's current location and moment are determined by preceding actions and constraints."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e9f17dfb333219cce1353f879de8deae</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CONNAISSANCES SÉMANTIQUES (SEMANTIC KNOWLEDGE)&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The integrated, abstract understanding of concepts (e.g., what a 'birthdate' represents) that is disrupted when the brain's semantic hub is damaged."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-aed49b1357eab65a81ac84db1c48e9f8</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LIVRE D'ÉTIENNE KLEIN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Étienne Klein's book, also referenced as having the prefrontal cortex as its central subject."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DISETTE/FAMINE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A period of extreme scarcity of food, used as a hypothetical context to illustrate how the value and perception of basic necessities like turnips can change dramatically."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;NEURONES DE DÉLAI&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Delay neurons are neurons in the prefrontal cortex that encode the position of a reward and anticipate the response vector of movement; they are crucial for preparing upcoming actions and are central to the function of working memory."&lt;SEP&gt;"Neurons in the prefrontal cortex that encode information about reward location and anticipate responses during waiting periods, used as evidence in the argument for deliberative processes."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e9f17dfb333219cce1353f879de8deae&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736994c87df07b89d48f895b0862dfe</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;STUDIO&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The physical recording studio where the dialogue between Richard Lévy and Étienne Klein is taking place."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PARTIES BASSES DU CORTEX PRÉFRONTAL&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The low parts of the prefrontal cortex, in contact with the orbits, are where the hot part is located."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ANIMALITÉ&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Animality represents the base instincts and behaviors that emerge when the layer of civilization deteriorates, revealing our primal nature."&lt;SEP&gt;"Animality represents the primal, instinctual behaviors that become visible when the layer of 'civilization' (maintained by the prefrontal cortex) deteriorates due to aging or pathology."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LIBRE ARBITRE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Free will is discussed as a philosophical concept linked to the margin of freedom provided by the prefrontal cortex; even a minimal margin of maneuver constitutes freedom, allowing for voluntary actions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-f736994c87df07b89d48f895b0862dfe</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;TRAITEMENT SUCCESSIF&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Successive processing refers to the brain's hierarchical method of analyzing information through progressively complex stages, from basic features to integrated perception."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cd188b1ca7e68272621793f69c55fafa</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DÉPRESSION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A mental illness characterized by severe low mood, given as an example where brain function changes can be detected."&lt;SEP&gt;"A specific mental illness used as an example where functional brain imaging can detect alterations."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;INFÉRENCES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Inferences are logical deductions made during the cognitive level of empathy and theory of mind. They can be of multiple degrees (third, fourth order) and are crucial for complex social understanding."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CERVEAU&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The brain is discussed as an organ that enables humans to transcend immediate perception, buffer time, and engage in abstraction, leading to discoveries beyond sensory input."&lt;SEP&gt;"The brain is the central organ discussed, with emphasis on its development, structure (like prefrontal cortex), and functions like building social norms."&lt;SEP&gt;"The brain is the central organ discussed, with its structures and functions related to handshakes and neurodegenerative diseases."&lt;SEP&gt;"The brain is the central organ of the nervous system that processes sensory information, integrates it, and creates perception; it is composed of structures like the cerebral cortex, neurons, and white matter."&lt;SEP&gt;"The brain is the organ responsible for cognitive functions, discussed in the context of adolescent development, particularly the maturation timeline of the prefrontal cortex and its implications for reasoning, inhibition, and emotional regulation."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-ef9367e0b21550ebdb56758dc0bde39a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5a0e0f31ff75981ae7f4e27b231396b7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cd188b1ca7e68272621793f69c55fafa</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;NOURRISSON&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Infant, mentioned in the context of lacking social norms at birth, illustrating that norms are constructed during brain development."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MONDE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The world represents the external reality that is perceived and interpreted by the brain, which acts as the mediator between sensory inputs and conscious experience."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cd188b1ca7e68272621793f69c55fafa</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;TROUBLES COGNITIFS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Cognitive disorders resulting from brain lesions or dysfunctions, as explained by Richard Lévy."&lt;SEP&gt;"Cognitive disorders resulting from brain lesions or dysfunctions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CONVENTION SOCIALE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Social convention refers to automatic gestures like handshakes that are governed by social norms and involve complex brain processes."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-ef9367e0b21550ebdb56758dc0bde39a</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ORBITES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The orbits are the bony cavities in the skull that contain the eyes; the text mentions the lower parts of the prefrontal cortex are in contact with them, indicating an anatomical location reference."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CONVERSATION SCIENTIFIQUE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The event where Étienne Klein interviews Richard Lévy about neurology and mental health."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ORGANISMES BIOLOGIQUES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Biological organisms are discussed as entities whose primary goal is survival, serving as a baseline against which human behavior, driven by abstract values, is contrasted."&lt;SEP&gt;"Biological organisms are living entities whose primary goal is survival and maintaining homeostasis within themselves and their species."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;JEAN MOULIN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Jean Moulin is a famous French resistant cited as an example of someone whose decision to resist was driven by his values, illustrating the concept of decision-making based on reward and punishment avoidance."&lt;SEP&gt;"Jean Moulin is a renowned French resistance fighter used as an example by Richard Lévy to demonstrate how individuals can act based on abstract values like altruism, even at the cost of personal survival."&lt;SEP&gt;"Jean Moulin was a prominent French Resistance leader during World War II, known for unifying various resistance groups. He was tortured and died in Nazi custody."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ÉPILEPSIE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A neurological disorder briefly mentioned at the end of the dialogue."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SURVIE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Survival is presented as a fundamental drive for all biological organisms, including humans, but humans also pursue other goals like homeostasis and abstract values."&lt;SEP&gt;"Survival refers to the fundamental biological imperative for organisms to continue living and avoiding death."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DÉMENCE SÉMANTIQUE (SEMANTIC DEMENTIA)&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A neurodegenerative disease affecting the brain's major semantic hub, leading to an inability to understand objects, words, and abstract concepts like 'date of birth,' while automatic behaviors remain intact."&lt;SEP&gt;"Semantic dementia is a neurodegenerative disease affecting the brain's major semantic hub, leading to an inability to understand objects, words, and concepts despite intact automatic functions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-aed49b1357eab65a81ac84db1c48e9f8</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;RÉCOMPENSE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Reward is a key concept in the experiment; delay neurons in the prefrontal cortex encode the location of a reward, motivating the animal's future action and decision."&lt;SEP&gt;"Reward is a positive value attributed to situations or objects that motivates behavior to approach them."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-f736994c87df07b89d48f895b0862dfe&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;VALEUR&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Value refers to the significance or worth attributed to objects or situations, which according to the text, fundamentally guides behavior and decision-making."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;IMAGERIE FONCTIONNELLE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Functional imaging technique mentioned as a means to detect brain function alterations, e.g., in depression."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;VALEURS CONTEXTUALISÉES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Contextualized values are those that are relativized based on changing circumstances, such as turnips becoming valuable during famine, enabled by prefrontal cortex activity."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MÉMOIRE DE TRAVAIL&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Working memory is the cognitive system that maintains and manipulates information in anticipation of a future action; it is described as an a priori activity that determines action and provides degrees of freedom."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-f736994c87df07b89d48f895b0862dfe</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PERCEPTION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Perception is described as subjective and shaped by individual experiences and biological systems, influencing how we understand the world."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BOSONS DE HIGGS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Higgs bosons are mentioned as an example of things that are not directly perceivable but have been discovered through the brain's abstract capabilities."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SUBSTANCE BLANCHE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"White matter is a component of the brain consisting of myelinated axons that facilitate communication between different brain regions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cd188b1ca7e68272621793f69c55fafa</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;VALEURS ABSTRAITES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Abstract values are human-created concepts like altruism and self-abnegation that can override basic survival instincts and are processed in the brain similarly to concrete values."&lt;SEP&gt;"Abstract values are non-material concepts like altruism, abnegation, and honor, which humans create and adjust to, sometimes overriding basic biological drives."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;WASHINGTON&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Washington D.C. is the capital of the United States and a center of political power."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;TECHNICIEN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A technician present in the studio, mentioned as someone Richard Lévy might observe while explaining his point about deliberating action."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LA MÈRE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The mother is an example used by Richard Lévy to illustrate the concept of mentalization. She infers her child's success or failure on the Bac exam by observing the child's facial expression."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DIALOGUE ENTRE RICHARD LÉVY ET ÉTIENNE KLEIN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A conversation in which Richard Lévy and Étienne Klein discuss perception, the brain, time, and abstraction, exploring how humans can discover imperceptible realities."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DYSFONCTIONNEMENT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
