</node>
<node id="&quot;CERVEAU HUMAIN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The human brain is described as the organ that processes both concrete and abstract values using similar neural structures, with the prefrontal cortex playing a key role in contextualizing values."&lt;SEP&gt;"The human brain is the central organ of the nervous system, responsible for processing both basic drives (like taste for sweet/salty) and abstract values through similar neural structures."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BRAIN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The central organ of the nervous system responsible for constructing perception, thought, and action. The text discusses how it processes sensory information to create a coherent experience of the world."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0f56e3dd7a20b73152355d96bd750de5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;IMITATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Imitation is the first phase in developing empathy, facilitated by mirror neurons. It allows understanding and replication of another's actions, such as a smile generating a smile."&lt;SEP&gt;"Imitation is the initial phase of empathy where individuals mirror others' actions, facilitated by mirror neurons."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ACTION FUTURE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Future action, which becomes possible through the brain's ability to delay time, deliberate, and anticipate consequences."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;STRUCTURES D'ACTION / NEURONES MIROIRS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Action structures or mirror neurons, brain mechanisms involved in imitation, appearing early in a child's life and contributing to empathy."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MALADES QUI S'IGNORENT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A phrase used by Richard Lévy to describe adolescents, implying they are 'patients who are unaware of being ill,' metaphorically referring to their incomplete brain maturation and resulting social behavior."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PITIÉ-SALPÊTRIÈRE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A hospital with a behavioral neurology unit that fosters collaboration between neurologists and psychiatrists."&lt;SEP&gt;"A major hospital in Paris hosting a behavioral neurology unit that practices integrated neuropsychiatric care."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;TROUS NOIRS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Black holes are mentioned as an example of things that are not directly perceivable but have been discovered through the brain's abstract capabilities."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ALTRUISME&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Altruism is given as a prime example of an abstract value that can compel actions contrary to individual organic well-being but aligned with higher principles."&lt;SEP&gt;"Altruism is the principle or practice of selfless concern for the well-being of others, often considered an abstract value."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ANIMAL&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The animal is a subject in a neuroscience experiment where its prefrontal cortex activity is monitored during a waiting period; its ability to choose a direction is impaired when specific neurons are destroyed, illustrating the role of working memory in preparing actions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-f736994c87df07b89d48f895b0862dfe</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ÉDITIONS ALBAIN MICHEL&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A publishing house that published Richard Lévy's book titled 'Cortex'."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0f56e3dd7a20b73152355d96bd750de5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;STÉPHANE CHARPIER&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Author of the book 'Le cauchemar de Descartes,' which argues that free will is a fiction and that decisions are made by unconscious neural activity before conscious awareness."&lt;SEP&gt;"Stéphane Charpier is a neuroscientist and author of 'Le cauchemar de Descartes', which discusses free will and neuroscience."&lt;SEP&gt;"Stéphane Charpier is an author referenced at the end of the conversation, who wrote a book titled 'Le cauchemar de Descartes' concerning free will, potentially offering a contrasting perspective to Richard Lévy's views."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e9f17dfb333219cce1353f879de8deae&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HOMÉOSTASIE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Homeostasis is described as a state of internal well-being that organisms strive to maintain, and in humans, abstract values can become part of this homeostatic adjustment."&lt;SEP&gt;"Homeostasis is the physiological process by which organisms maintain a stable internal environment, a state of internal well-being."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ASIE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Asia is mentioned as one of the habitats of elephants in Richard Lévy's explanation of semantic knowledge distribution in the brain."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cef3ed8b278fc8ecffbe23ed1293fa7a</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LE CAUCHEMAR DE DESCARTES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A book publication event by Stéphane Charpier, which presents the argument against free will, sparking intellectual debate."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e9f17dfb333219cce1353f879de8deae</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ADOLESCENT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Adolescents are young individuals whose brains, particularly the prefrontal cortex, are not fully developed. They tend to adhere to peer norms rather than parental norms, and their cognitive capacities, such as inhibition, are still maturing."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5a0e0f31ff75981ae7f4e27b231396b7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;TRAC&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Stage fright is described as a defect in emotion regulation where overwhelming emotions stun cognitive abilities, leading to a decrease in performance due to the failure of the prefrontal cortex to properly regulate emotional signals."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-f736994c87df07b89d48f895b0862dfe</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CONNAISSANCES ABSTRAITES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Abstract knowledge, described as less stable, finer connections in the brain's network that are the first to decline in a progressive disease."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;RUTABAGAS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Rutabagas are mentioned alongside turnips as an example of food that becomes highly valued in a context of scarcity and famine."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ADOLESCENCE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Adolescence is a developmental stage where the brain is not fully matured. Adolescents are described as rebelling against parental norms and adopting new norms from their peers, indicating an ongoing cognitive and social development process."&lt;SEP&gt;"Adolescence is a life stage where individuals rebel against parental norms and adopt peer norms, reflecting incomplete brain maturation according to Richard Lévy."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ABSTRACTION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Abstraction refers to the ability to imagine things that are not concretely present, such as fundamental particles or future possibilities, enabled by the brain's prefrontal cortex."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CROYANCES ET VALEURS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Beliefs and values are abstract constructs built upon theory of mind and inferences. They form the basis of our morality and social norms, residing in the highest cognitive layer."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CORTEX PRÉFRONTAL&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A brain region critical for decision-making and internal drive; its integrity is argued to be necessary for degrees of freedom, as its destruction leads to environmental dependency."&lt;SEP&gt;"A region of the brain highlighted by Richard Lévy as crucial for opening up time, enabling deliberation, anticipation, and imagination of non-existent things."&lt;SEP&gt;"The prefrontal cortex is a brain region divided into cold and hot parts, responsible for functions such as planning, reasoning, motivation, emotion regulation, and vegetative functions like hunger and thirst."&lt;SEP&gt;"The prefrontal cortex is a brain region involved in decision-making and complex actions; it is mentioned in the context of handshakes and its degeneration in dementia."&lt;SEP&gt;"The prefrontal cortex is a brain region responsible for higher cognitive functions, including empathy and social norms; its deterioration leads to loss of civilized behavior."&lt;SEP&gt;"The prefrontal cortex is a brain region responsible for higher-order functions, including the relativization and contextualization of values, allowing humans to override automatic absolute values."&lt;SEP&gt;"The prefrontal cortex is a brain region that matures late (around 25-35 years) and is responsible for cognitive style and executive functions."&lt;SEP&gt;"The prefrontal cortex is a brain region where delay neurons are active; it is responsible for working memory, anticipates and prepares future actions, and provides a margin of freedom between perception and action, forming the neural basis for voluntary action and aspects of free will."&lt;SEP&gt;"The prefrontal cortex is a brain structure responsible for the highest levels of abstraction, including beliefs, values, social norms, and morality. Its function is fragile and can decline with normal aging or pathology, leading to a loss of 'civilization'."&lt;SEP&gt;"The prefrontal cortex is a region of the brain associated with higher-order cognitive functions, including the creation, contextualization, and relativization of abstract values."&lt;SEP&gt;"The prefrontal cortex is a region of the brain that is dual in nature, associated with both reason (cold, rational planning) and soul (hot, regulating internal sensations, emotions, mood, and motivation). It matures around age 28-35, and its development is crucial for cognitive control."&lt;SEP&gt;"The prefrontal cortex is described as the brain's conductor, organizing thoughts and behaviors. Its dysfunction leads to symptoms like apathy, disinhibition, and lack of motivation in neurodegenerative diseases."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e9f17dfb333219cce1353f879de8deae&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ef9367e0b21550ebdb56758dc0bde39a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736994c87df07b89d48f895b0862dfe&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5a0e0f31ff75981ae7f4e27b231396b7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cef3ed8b278fc8ecffbe23ed1293fa7a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DÉMENCE FRONTALE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Frontotemporal dementia is a neurodegenerative disease affecting the frontal and temporal lobes, leading to behavioral disorders and apathy."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-ef9367e0b21550ebdb56758dc0bde39a</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MONDE EXTÉRIEUR&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The external world, whose perception is described as largely subjective and filtered through individual experience and biological systems."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PARTIE CHAUDE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The hot part of the prefrontal cortex, located near the orbits, is responsible for hot functions like motivation, emotion regulation, and vegetative functions, and is present in all mammals."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;RAISON&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Reason is the cold, rational aspect of the prefrontal cortex, involved in logical thinking, organization, and planning. It is contrasted with the soul (âme) in the dual nature of the prefrontal cortex."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5a0e0f31ff75981ae7f4e27b231396b7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MALADIES MENTALES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Mental illnesses are discussed in the context of neurological dysfunctions, with the question raised of whether all mental illnesses are linked to malfunctions in the brain."&lt;SEP&gt;"Mental illnesses, conditions affecting thinking, behavior, and emotion, discussed in relation to brain dysfunctions."&lt;SEP&gt;"Mental illnesses; discussed in terms of their potential biological origins and the challenges of diagnosis."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-f736994c87df07b89d48f895b0862dfe&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;EMPATHIE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Empathy consists of a basic emotional level (based on imitation and mentalization) and a higher cognitive/computational level (based on theory of mind and inference). It is fundamental to human relationships."&lt;SEP&gt;"Empathy is a human relational capacity consisting of an emotional level (based on imitation and mentalization) and a cognitive level (involving theory of mind)."&lt;SEP&gt;"Empathy is a psychological construct built through imitation and other mechanisms, crucial for social norms."&lt;SEP&gt;"Empathy is an emotional capacity that can be lost when the hot part of the prefrontal cortex is impaired, as illustrated by the example of a serial killer."&lt;SEP&gt;"Empathy is the ability to understand others' emotions and intentions, and its loss is mentioned as a consequence of prefrontal cortex damage."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-cef3ed8b278fc8ecffbe23ed1293fa7a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BIAIS COGNITIFS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Cognitive biases, described by Richard Lévy as unconscious processes that constrain human thinking and determine certain actions, limiting free will."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e9f17dfb333219cce1353f879de8deae</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PRIMATES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CATEGORY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A biological order to which humans belong, noted by Richard Lévy as having a distinctive prefrontal cortex structure."&lt;SEP&gt;"Primates are a group of mammals that have both hot and cold parts of the prefrontal cortex, with humans showing a spectacular development of the cold part."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;RICHARD LÉVY&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">Richard Lévy is a neurologist and neuroscientist who serves as a professor of neurology at Sorbonne Université and a researcher at the Institut du Cerveau, where he heads the Frontlab team. A significant portion of his expertise and clinical work focuses on the prefrontal cortex, neurodegenerative diseases such as Alzheimer's, frontotemporal dementia, and semantic dementia. He explains the biological and neurological basis of mental illnesses, advocating for closer collaboration between the fields of neurology and psychiatry.

His research investigates high-level brain functions including decision-making, creativity, working memory, and the preparatory role of "delay neurons." He delves into complex cognitive and social mechanisms, explaining concepts like empathy, mirror neurons, mentalization (theory of mind), and the role of the prefrontal cortex in adhering to social norms and civilization. This extends to practical discussions on topics like adolescent brain development—noting the late maturation of the prefrontal cortex and its implications for cognition and behavior—and even the neurological complexity behind simple actions like a handshake.

Richard Lévy also engages deeply with philosophical questions, defending a nuanced view of free will. He argues that while human choices are constrained by senses, physical laws</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e9f17dfb333219cce1353f879de8deae&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0f56e3dd7a20b73152355d96bd750de5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ef9367e0b21550ebdb56758dc0bde39a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-831d96d12ba52ebdde5127ea0b27984d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-696e6532b6fd5570de4d3650523b608e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736994c87df07b89d48f895b0862dfe&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1161f1eb6f483238105e2fc6b85fde00&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b6c33ae2e365cd0a1d3d8102409d7912&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5a0e0f31ff75981ae7f4e27b231396b7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cef3ed8b278fc8ecffbe23ed1293fa7a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b3da432a99878091a368929c8cf97145&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cd188b1ca7e68272621793f69c55fafa&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9ebbd597f1f269b6bb0cdf9434076464&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-aed49b1357eab65a81ac84db1c48e9f8</data>
</node>
